      <sourceDesc>
        <msDesc>
          <msIdentifier>
            <repository ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/INS0809MJR">John Rylands Library</repository>
            <collection>Ethiopic Manuscripts</collection>
            <idno facs="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/iiif/MS-ETHIOPIC-00004" corresp="https://www.digitalcollections.manchester.ac.uk/iiif/MS-ETHIOPIC-00004">Ethiopic MS 4</idno>
          </msIdentifier>
          <msContents>
            <summary>
              <p>A Deggwā (Antiphonary) with musical notation for the whole year. The manuscript also contains the Ṣoma deggwā (Antiphony for Lent), which is somewhat
                exceptional. The manuscript was copied during the reign of Emperor Iyasu II (1730 to 1755).</p>
            </summary>
            <msItem xml:id="ms_i1">
              <title>Deggwā</title>
              
              <textLang mainLang="gez">Geez</textLang>
              <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.1">
                <locus from="3r" to="4v">3r-4v</locus>
                <title xml:lang="gez">አንቀጸ ፡ ሃሌታ ፡ እምዮሐንስ ፡ እስከ ፡ ዮሐንስ ፡ ግዕዝ ፡ ወበኵሉ ፡ መዋዕል፡</title>
                <note>Table of Hallelujahs with Musical Notation</note>
                <incipit>ዩበ፩ ፡ ሃሌ ፤ ሉያ ፤ ይትፌሣሕ ። | ዩበ፩ ፡ ሃሌ ፤ ሉያ ፤ ዴግንዋ ። | ዩበ፩ ፡ ሃሌ ፤ ሉያ ፤ ይስጠዎ ። </incipit>
              </msItem>
              <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.2">
                <locus from="5r" to="78v">5r-78v</locus>
                <title>Deggwā (first part)</title>
                <incipit>በስመ ፡ ሥሉስ ፡ ቅዱስ ፡ ዘበትሥልስ[ት ፡] ይትወለድ ፡ ዘኢይትፈለጥ ፡ ወኢይትበዓድ ፤ ዘ፩ይጼለይ ፤ ወ፩ይስገድ ። ጸሐፍነ ፡ እንከ ፡ ማኅልያተ ፡ (sic) ያሬድ ፤ ዘይደምጽ ፡ ከመ ፡ ነጐድጓድ ። ወኃይለ ፡ ቃሉ ፡ ንዑድ ። ወጣዕመ ፡ ዜማ
                  (b) ሁ ፡ ፍድፉድ ። አስራበ ፡ ስብሐት ፡ ዕሉድ ። ሠርጐ ፡ ኢትዮጵያ ፡ መስተዛውዓ ፡ ካህናት ፡ በመንፈሳዊት ፡ ዐፀድ ። መስተፍሥሔ ፡ አልባቢሆሙ [] ለሕዝብ ፡ ክቡድ ። ይገይሱ ፡ (c) ኀበ ፡ ዘመለኮት ፡ ማሕፈድ ። ክብራነ ፡ ዘመድ ፡ እለ ፡
                  ሐፀኖሙ ፡ አሐዱ ፡ ጕንድ ። ዝንቱ ፡ መጽሐፍ ፡ ዘስሙ ፡ በርበሬ " ወጽሕፈቱኒ ፡ ኮነ ፡ በመዋዕሊሁ ፡ ለንጉሥነ ፡ ኢያሱ ። ። ።</incipit>
                <note>First part of Deggwā from ዘዮሐንስ ፡ to ዋዜማ ፡ ዘገብረ ፡ መንፈስ ፡ ቅዱስ ፡.</note>
                <note>The name of the book is given as Berbere (sic).</note>
              </msItem>
              <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.3">
                <locus from="80r" to="125v">80r-125v</locus>
                <title xml:lang="gez-Latn-x-lc">Ṣoma deggwā. ጾመ ፡ ድጓ</title>
                <note>Antiphony for Lent</note>
              </msItem>
              <msItem xml:id="ms_i1.4">
                <locus from="127r" to="172r">127r-172r</locus>
                <title xml:lang="gez-Latn-x-lc">Deggwā (second part)</title>
                <note>From ዘፋሲካ to end.</note>
              </msItem>
            </msItem>
          </msContents>
          <physDesc>
            <objectDesc form="Codex">
              <supportDesc>
                <support>
                  <material key="parchment">Parchment</material> book block</support>
                <extent>173 folios: <dimensions type="leaf" unit="mm">
                  <height>225</height>
                  <width>210</width>
                </dimensions>
                  <dimensions type="outer" unit="mm">
                    <height>235</height>
                    <width>223</width>
                    <depth>84</depth>
                  </dimensions>
                </extent>
                <foliation>
                  <p>Modern pencil foliation in Arabic numerals on the upper right corner of each recto folio.</p>
                  <p>Unnumbered folio between folios 105v and 106r; folioation is missing between 105v and 106r; 128rv has been duplicated .</p>
                </foliation>
                <collation><p>Sections are composed primarily of 4 bifolios.</p></collation>
              </supportDesc>
              <layoutDesc>
                <layout columns="3" writtenLines="30">
                  <p>Three columns, 30 lines per leaf.</p>
                  <p>Folios have been pricked and scored to assist in writing, though on some folios the scoring lines are so heavy they are causing splits in the
                    parchment.</p></layout>
              </layoutDesc>
            </objectDesc>
            <handDesc test-plan="1">
              <handNote xml:id="h1" script="Ethiopic">
                <p>Written in a <term ana="#">Ge'ez</term> script, in black and red ink, by a single hand; very small excellent handwriting with musical notation.</p>
              </handNote>
            </handDesc>
            <additions>
              <p>On <locus from="1v" to="1v">1v</locus> pen trials.</p>
              <p>On <locus from="2r" to="2r">2r</locus> 'Hymns' and at the bottom an ornamental band in black ink.</p>
              <p>On <locus from="7r" to="7r">7r</locus> and throughout, marginalia minuscule corrections about 1 mm in height, in an excellent hand.</p>
            </additions>
            <bindingDesc>
              <binding contemporary="unknown" notBefore="1730" notAfter="1755">
                <decoNote xml:id="b1">Ethiopic binding. Exposed wooden boards, thick and smooth with a slight rounding of the three external edges. Parchment spine lining made of Ethiopic
                  manuscript waste, not adhered but slotted around the four sewing stations with 5 protruding flaps inside the covers. Front board has a vertical split down the
                  centre and has been repaired with three sets of looped thread. Leather remnants inside the boards of both boards suggest it may have been covered at some point. No
                  endbands extant. Unsupported sewing at 4 stations (two even pairs of sewing stations). The sewing is laced into the boards as an integral part of the sewing process
                  and is done in separate pairs with each pair sewn using a different thread. Sewing is broken between folios 87-88 and 88-95 is partially loose. Knots between folios
                  83-84 and 99-100 to secure sewing suggest it has been repaired, though this repair is failing.</decoNote>

                <decoNote xml:id="b2">Traditional two-part brown leather slip case. Split braid leather loop on the top of the box. Long carrying strap only remains attached on the right side with two
                  strips of leather. Blind tooled decoration. Fragile with damage to the leather and sewing starting to break along the joins.<dimensions type="satchel" unit="mm">
                  <height>280</height>
                  <width>250</width>
                  <depth>100</depth>
                </dimensions></decoNote>
                
              </binding>
            </bindingDesc>
          </physDesc>
          <history>
            <origin>
              <origDate calendar="gregorian" notBefore="1730" notAfter="1755" cert="high">1730-1755</origDate>
              <origPlace><country ref="http://vocab.getty.edu/page/tgn/7000489">Ethiopia</country></origPlace>
            </origin>
            <provenance>
              <p>A marginal note on <locus from="5r" to="5r">5r</locus> indicates the manuscript belonged at one time to the Church of the Saviour of the World
                located at <placeName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC0000">Āmba Maryam</placeName> (i.e. Magdala) and would have been taken by a member of the British army in
                <date>1867-1868</date>.</p></provenance>
            <provenance><p>Another marginal note on <locus from="172r" to="172r">172r</locus> indicates the manuscript belonged at one time to <origPlace ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/LOC0000">Lalībela</origPlace>. </p>
            </provenance>
            <provenance><p><name type="person" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/9985420" role="fmo"><persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS0000">James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford (1847-1913)</persName>
              </name>. The inner upper cover
              (pastedown) bears the armorial bookplate (Ex Libris) identifying the codex as having once been part of the Bibliotheca Lindesiana, the private library of the Lindsay
              family, Earls of Crawford and Balcarres | Armorial bookplate (Ex Libris): ARMS: Quarterly, 1st and 4th,
              Gules a fess chequy Argent and Azure; 2nd and 3rd, Or a lion rampant Gules, debruised of a ribbon in bend Sable. CREST: a swan’s head, neck, and wings proper, issuing
              from an antique ducal coronet Or. SUPPORTERS: two lions, rampant guardant Gules. MOTTO in Latin: Endure fort (Endure bravely) | Bibliotheca Lindesiana | pencilled: 5/G.
              Pencilled on left inner upper cover: Ethiopic MSS | No 4.</p>
            </provenance>
            <provenance><p>Purchased by <name type="person" role="dnr"><persName ref="https://betamasaheft.eu/PRS0000">Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908)</persName></name> in <date calendar="gregorian" when="1901">1901</date> from James Ludovic Lindsay, 26th Earl of Crawford
              (1847-1913).</p></provenance>
            <acquisition><p>Bequeathed by Enriqueta Rylands (1843–1908) in <date calendar="gregorian" when="1908">1908</date> to <name type="institution" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/152274029" role="own"><orgName type="display">The John Rylands Library</orgName></name>.</p>
            </acquisition>
          </history>
